{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5edc58cb-ca4f-48cb-a264-d041511e98ed","content":"There are no workflow files in this directory. Since I can't inspect your specific workflow, here's what you need to change to switch to **NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC)**:\n\n### 1. Configure NuGet.org\n- Go to **nuget.org → Manage Packages → Trusted Publishers**\n- Add a new **GitHub Actions** publisher policy, specifying your repo, branch/tag filters, and optionally the workflow/environment\n\n### 2. Update your workflow\n\n**Add OIDC permissions** to the job:\n```yaml\npermissions:\n  id-token: write   # Required for OIDC token\n  contents: read\n```\n\n**Replace** your current push step (which uses `secrets.NUGET_API_KEY`) with:\n```yaml\n- name: Push to NuGet\n  run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg \\\n    --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\nNo `--api-key` flag is needed — the OIDC token is exchanged automatically when the `dotnet` CLI detects the environment.\n\n> **Note:** As of .NET SDK 9+, `dotnet nuget push` supports OIDC natively. For older SDKs, you may need the [`nuget/setup-nuget`](https://github.com/NuGet/setup-nuget) action to handle token exchange.\n\n### 3. Remove the secret\nOnce verified, delete `NUGET_API_KEY` from your repo's **Settings → Secrets**.\n\nWant me to create a sample workflow file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0c5e1b50-17fe-4228-be8f-8bdd05b62b3b","outputTokens":371,"requestId":"E42C:1521A3:6AA4CCF:7301FCD:6A03CD37"},"id":"ae978043-1b2e-4fe0-969d-a7397ce064dc","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:00:49.245Z","parentId":"abaa5655-0472-4112-8e14-bbb8b3b222d9"}
